04586nam a2200757Ia 9789815104844DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20232023si     fo  d z      eng d  a97898151048447 a10.1355/97898151048442doi  a(DE-B1597)677638  a(OCoLC)1406084414  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  asicSG 4aBP40.5 7aSOC0520002bisacsh04a297.2/66223/eng/202311091 aSuryana, A'an, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIndonesia’s Moderate Muslim Websites and Their Fight Against Online Islamic Extremism /cA'an Suryana. 1aSingapore : bISEAS Publishing, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (36 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tFOREWORD -- tEXECUTIVE SUMMARY -- tINTRODUCTION -- tSOCIAL MEDIA AND RADICAL WEBSITES -- tTHE EFFECTIVENESS OF MODERATE WEBSITES -- tCHALLENGES IN FIGHTING ONLINE RADICALISM -- tTHE ROLE OF THE GOVERNMENT -- tCONCLUSION -- tREFERENCES0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIt is worrying that, in many cases in Indonesia, exposure to the Internet, especially social media, increases knowledge seekers’ religious radicalism. This exposure has not only resulted in increased radicalism but also compelled some individuals to turn to violence in the name of Islam. Moderate online media institutions have not been effective in counteracting the online dissemination of extremist religious content. The content disseminated by radical websites is still being popularly consumed, albeit those moderate Muslim websites have put in considerable effort to counteract radical narratives. This report argues that this ineffectiveness is due to structural and cultural challenges. The structural challenges include limited funding and sensitivity towards the policy of umbrella organizations. Cultural challenges include passiveness in corporate culture, alongside the “ivory tower” traditions among journalists which leaves them out of touch with Muslim communities. The government of Indonesia can assist moderate Muslim media websites in fighting radical narratives, for example, through better funding to them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aInternetxReligious aspectsxIslamzIndonesia. 0aInternetzIndonesiaxReligious aspectsxIslam. 0aIslamic fundamentalismzIndonesia. 0aMedia enterpriseszIndonesiaxFinance. 0aRadicalism in mass media. 0aRadicalismzIndonesia. 0aSocial mediaxReligious aspectsxIslamzIndonesia. 0aSocial mediazIndonesiaxReligious aspectsxIslam. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2023 Part 2z978311117804208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2023 Englishz978311131926108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2023z9783111318806oZDB-23-DSL40uhttps://doi.org/10.1355/978981510484440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789815104844423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789815104844/original  a978-3-11-117804-2  DG Plus PP Package 2023 Part 2b2023  a978-3-11-131926-1  EBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2023 Englishb2023  a978-3-11-131929-2  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishb2023  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGGb2023  aZDB-23-DSLb2023